Fix DafnySet<T>::disjoint() calling a non-existent member

The C++ runtime header shipped with Dafny 4.11.0 does not compile. Any
program translated with `dafny translate cpp` fails at the first include,
because DafnySet<T>::disjoint() calls other.find(elt), and DafnySet<T>
exposes no find member -- the underlying std::set is the member `set`.

Every sibling method in the same class already goes through `.set`
(contains() uses set.find(t), Union() uses ret.set.insert(...)), so this
is a plain omission rather than a design difference.

Reproduced on Dafny 4.11.0 (Homebrew) with g++ -std=c++14, -std=c++17,
-std=c++20 and clang++ -std=c++17, all giving:

    DafnyRuntime.h:550:23: error: no member named 'find' in 'DafnySet<T>'
      550 |             if (other.find(elt) != other.set.end()) {
          |                 ~~~~~ ^

With this one-token fix applied, a translated "hello world" compiles,
links, and runs.

--- a/DafnyRuntime.h
+++ b/DafnyRuntime.h
@@ -547,7 +547,7 @@

     bool disjoint(const DafnySet<T>& other) {
         for (auto const& elt:set) {
-            if (other.find(elt) != other.set.end()) {
+            if (other.set.find(elt) != other.set.end()) {
                 return false;
             }
         }
